  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe vector-combine pass
crashes with a SIGSEGV while iterating over instructions in a basic block
using make_early_inc_range. The debug log shows that after a fold, the pass
proceeds to erase multiple instructions (not just the currently-processed
instruction). This can invalidate the underlying intrusive list iterator and
lead to dereferencing freed nodes. The stack trace confirms the failure
occurs during list iteration (ilist iterator operator++/operator*), pointing
to instruction list corruption due to erasure during iteration.\n\n2.
Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug-only log shows these steps:\n- Folding and
replacing an 'and' instruction with a constant vector containing poison
lanes.\n- Erasing the 'and' instruction.\n- Erasing other related
instructions: the insertelement, phi, and the vector.reduce
intrinsic.\nImmediately after that, the pass visits a <badref> call with
<null operand!>, indicating that IR has been corrupted. This timing aligns
with the first transformation point in VectorCombine::run, specifically the
instruction scanning loop.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe main scan loop
uses:\n  for (Instruction &I : make_early_inc_range(BB)) {\n    ...
MadeChange |= FoldInst(I);\n  }\nmake_early_inc_range only guarantees safe
erasure of the current element while iterating, but eraseInstruction() can
remove arbitrary other instructions in the same basic block via
RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions on operands. Erasing non-current
instructions during iteration can invalidate the iterator for the next
instruction, leading to use-after-free and the observed SIGSEGV. This is
corroborated by the crash location and the subsequent visitation of a
\"<badref>\" instruction.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\nReplace the
early-increment range iteration with a two-phase approach: collect
instruction pointers into a vector first, then iterate over that stable
snapshot. This avoids iterator invalidation when erasing any instructions
during the processing phase.\n\nEdit at
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp lines 4517-4526:\n\n-
Current:\n  4516   bool MadeChange = false;\n  4517   for (BasicBlock &BB :
F) {\n  4518     // Ignore unreachable basic blocks.\n  4519     if
(!DT.isReachableFromEntry(&BB))\n  4520       continue;\n  4521     // Use
early increment range so that we can erase instructions in loop.\n  4522
for (Instruction &I : make_early_inc_range(BB)) {\n  4523       if
(I.isDebugOrPseudoInst())\n  4524         continue;\n  4525       MadeChange
|= FoldInst(I);\n  4526     }\n  4527   }\n\n- Replace with:\n  4516   bool
MadeChange = false;\n  4517   for (BasicBlock &BB : F) {\n  4518     //
Ignore unreachable basic blocks.\n  4519     if
(!DT.isReachableFromEntry(&BB))\n  4520       continue;\n  4521     //
Collect a stable snapshot of instructions to avoid iterator invalidation\n
4522     // when folds erase non-current instructions.\n  4523
SmallVector<Instruction *, 64> Insts;\n  4524
Insts.reserve(BB.size());\n  4525     for (Instruction &I : BB)\n  4526
Insts.push_back(&I);\n  4527     for (Instruction *IP : Insts) {\n  4528
if (IP->isDebugOrPseudoInst())\n  4529         continue;\n  4530
MadeChange |= FoldInst(*IP);\n  4531     }\n  4532   }\n\nThis change
maintains functionality while ensuring that any erasures during
FoldInst/eraseInstruction do not invalidate the iteration, since we're
iterating over a separate container of raw pointers captured before
transformations.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by erasing
non-current instructions in a basic block while iterating over it using
make_early_inc_range. By first collecting instruction pointers into a
SmallVector and iterating over this stable snapshot, we avoid iterator
invalidation and prevent the use-after-free that leads to the SIGSEGV. The
rest of the pass logic, including the Worklist-driven processing, remains
unchanged, and the fix should stabilize the pass for this and similar cases
where transformations recursively delete multiple instructions within the
same block.",
